If there's such a thing as perfection on the
basketball court, Dwyane Wade came as close as possible Tuesday
night.
article.headline: Wade hits first 11 shots, finishes with 28 points
article.linkText: Wade on fire in Marquette's rout of Eastern Illinois
article.story:
MILWAUKEE (AP) -- If there's such a thing as perfection on the
basketball court, Dwyane Wade came as close as possible Tuesday
night.

	   Wade set a school record by hitting his first 11 shots, all in
the first half and all while guarding one of the nation's best
shooters as he sparked No. 13 Marquette's 97-74 rout of Eastern
Illinois.

	   ''Dwyane's first half was incredible,'' Golden Eagles coach Tom
Crean marveled. ''I mean, to not miss a shot, to continue to
rebound the ball and to be guarding the other team's best player?
That's a lot of work in 20 minutes.''

	   Wade took his latest spectacular showing in stride.

	   ''I guess I can't shoot any better,'' he said. ''But I can play
better.''

	   Wade, who finished with 28 points on 13-of-16 shooting, broke
the school record of consecutive shots made to start a game when he
swished a 15-foot jumper for a 46-32 lead over the Panthers (1-3).

	   Larry McNeill sank his first 10 shots against Kentucky in 1971,
and Terry Reason did the same against Iona in 1983.

	   ''I've been a Dwyane Wade admirer for a long time and I thought
he played exceptionally well,'' Panthers coach Rick Samuels said.
''And this may sound crazy, but we defended pretty hard in the
first half ... and they still shot 70 percent. That was an
exceptional display.''

	   Robert Jackson scored 18 of his 22 points after halftime and
grabbed nine rebounds as the Golden Eagles (4-0) extended their
home winning streak to 19, their longest in seven seasons.

	   Wade's first shot of the second half clanked off the rim.

	   Wade's highly anticipated matchup with Henry Domercant, a senior
who was second in the nation in scoring a year ago with a
26.4-point average, was a mismatch in the first half, although
Domercant finished with 27 points on 10-of-17 shooting.

	   It shouldn't be a surprise that he had such a good offensive
showing while having to defend Domercant, Wade suggested.

	   ''No, it gives you a little more juice,'' Wade said.

	   Wade had three smooth dunks off steals in the first seven
minutes and hit everything from pull-up jumpers to off-balance bank
shots.

	   ''I mean, we tried. It was a pretty good effort on our part, I
thought,'' Samuels said. ''He's pretty good.''

	   By the time Domercant got warmed up to score 11 first-half
points, the Golden Eagles were well on their way to victory. But
Domercant came out hot in the second half, scoring seven quick
points. And with Wade on the bench with his third foul, the
Panthers began chipping away.

	   That's when Jackson, a 6-foot-10, 260-pound senior transfer from
Mississippi State who has provided Marquette with a rare inside
game, took over, scoring four of five Marquette baskets as the
Golden Eagles built their lead to 86-60.

	   R.J. Reynolds added 23 points for the Panthers, who were outshot
62 percent to 42 percent.

	   Travis Diener and Steve Novak each had 11 points for Marquette,
and Scott Merritt added 10 for the Golden Eagles.

	   Wade, a junior who was a partial qualifier as a freshman, has
scored in double figures 35 times in 36 games for Marquette, which
hasn't been ranked this high this early in a season since Al
McGuire's 1977 team won the national championship.

	   Eastern Illinois has played all four of its games on the road.

	   ''Not making any excuses, but our kids have been home 35 hours
in the last 11 days,'' Samuels said. ''We've got from Boise to
Gainesville to Chicago. We were in short sleeves four days ago. Now
we're freezing up here in Milwaukee.''
